<div id="review_28944891" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28944891" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/155663-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581956036p2/155663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28944891?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/155663-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/155663-david?shelf=science">science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/155663-david?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28944891" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6349902141363319614">I am a scientist, and I found much of this book quite fascinating. The book certainly isn&apos;t comprehensive in any sense of the word--in fact it seems to roam in a semi-random sort of way; but the author&apos;s sense of humor and attention to colorful historical facts kept my interest from beginning to end.<br/><br/>One of the themes of this book, is that when someone comes up with with a new discovery, there are three stages before it is accepted:<br/>1) Nobody believes it. <br/>2) Nobody thinks it is important<br/>3) It gets</span>
  <span id="freeText6349902141363319614" style="display:none">I am a scientist, and I found much of this book quite fascinating. The book certainly isn't comprehensive in any sense of the word--in fact it seems to roam in a semi-random sort of way; but the author's sense of humor and attention to colorful historical facts kept my interest from beginning to end.<br /><br />One of the themes of this book, is that when someone comes up with with a new discovery, there are three stages before it is accepted:<br />1) Nobody believes it. <br />2) Nobody thinks it is important<br />3) It gets attributed to the wrong person.<br />These three stages come up again and again in this book. I guess it can be attributed to the fact that most scientists--and most people--are, at heart, conservative in nature. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6349902141363319614" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


